name: Lexi Cinema
text: The Lexi Cinema truly is the archetypal great little place. Along Chamberlayne Road, past the gothic splendour of the Catholic Church of the Transfiguration, is Kensal Rise's Constitutional Club. Its old hall has taken on a remarkable new life. Inside is a gorgeous little cinema. With seats for 40 or so, it's hugely intimate and cosy, but with a sound system installed by the same chap who does U2's tours and crisp digital projection, it's serious about the experience. Dangling from the ceiling is a mesmerising lighting installation by Bruce Munro, fading gently from one hue to another. It's a proper community here – half the audience either know each other or know the Lexi staff, and there's a true feel of locals. Everyone chats before the film. The seats are comfy, with candlelit tables at the front, and each film is personally introduced, harking back to an era where you didn't just go and see a movie, you went out to the cinema. There are often Q&As with directors or added bits of theatre here and there; they even do a night where the New York Met Opera is beamed live to the assembled, black-tied, admirers. What really sets the Lexi apart is its mission. All the profits, from tickets to drinks to popcorn, go to a South African charity called The Sustainability Institute – which means they're probably the only cinema in London which actively encourages you to drink wine whilst watching a film. We'll take that. We won't say more, just go.

text: the horniman museum in london is one of the most interesting and informative museums i have come across on my travels. museum curators have a knack for engaging the public of london in a way that allows them to explore the diversity within the city using highly accessible means, for example, a recent exhibition titled 'the body adorned' explored the diversity within london through the topic of clothing, tattoos and jewellery. it is truely a space dedicated to exploring the social world around us enhanced greatly by the employment of community groups and guest curators from around the world to interpret object and displays. a trip to the horniman museum will allow the visitor to explore global history and practices through an intercultural lense allowing you to question what you know about other cultural communities. highly enjoyable and highly recommended.

name: Horniman Museum & Gardens
text: Since I can remember, the Horniman Museum has been a special place for me. A treasure on our doorsteps, I think it can often be overlooked by many in the borough. I have vivid memories of spending what seemed like hours staring through the glass at all sorts of stuffed animals that I'd never seen before - the animals were a lot bigger when I was six years old! Then as I got older I'd be taken there on school trips to study more about our current class projects such as Anicent Egypt and biodiversity. Not many children are fortunate enough to have such an important cultural resource like the Horniman Museum anywhere near them. I last visited the Museum during the summer last year during the build-up to the London Olympics to see 'The Body Adorned: Dressing London', an exhibition which explored the question of what we wear and why. It proved to me how London embraces diversity and that different cultures, however distinct, complement each other in this city and make us richer people. I would recommend going to visit for a long day during the weekend in July/August when you can enjoy a variety of events which take place in the Gardens, like classical concerts and latin dance performances - a great way to end a trip to the museum!

name: Tate Modern
text: The great big brown brick-clad building on the south-bank of the Thames contains one of the world's most celebrated collections of modern art. I've just returned from yet another mind-nourishing wander around it's huge halls. There are two things I've always enjoyed most about the Tate. Firstly, the thematic presentation of it's work. Rather than chronological periods, the art is grouped into collections, such as 'states of flux' and 'poetry and dreams', which place old classics in new context and allow visitors to listen in on the interesting conversations going on between the art and artists across large periods of time. Secondly, it is constantly changing. No two trips to the gallery are ever the same. Walls have moved. Grand new projects have been set up in Turbine Hall. Art has disappeared and new work has emerged. Read more about my experience and see my photos on Triptease.

name: Curwen & New Academy Gallery
text: Such a wonderful gallery! My favourite in central London.I've bought a number of lovely art works from here over the years and always been very happy with them.The director, Jill, is so helpful and is always brimming with information about all the artists. The gallery seem to have a very personal and unintimidating approach to selling art, not like many other galleries I go to in London.I've also heard that they have quite a reputation for their work with businesses, art hire for offices and such like, which has been highly recommended by a few of my colleagues (although I've not looked into this myself).All round a lovely spot to pick up some quality affordable art work, as well as a few more expensive classic pieces for the occasional indulgence!

address: 13 Lincoln's Inn Fields, London, United Kingdom
name: Sir John Soane's Museum
text: One of my favourite museums in London. Soane was a magnificent architect and his design of his house has some great uses of spaces. You'll see light through glass illuminating sculptures, peer at objects through open spaces and see crafted mouldings that come alive at different angles. Soane really did create an immersive physical experience out of the space. His efforts to create and furnish his house with clutter and objects from around the world means you'll always see something new. I'm a kleptomaniac too, so it's nice to see someone keeping a range of such eclectic objects that all have relevance and meaning. It's great to spend an hour here then come back every year. Every time you'll see more objects and bits of curiosity. It's free too and near a great pub called The Ship Tavern on Gate St that's well worth a visit- decent real ale and pies. Top tip: the first Tuesday of every month is open by candlelight. Great for a date night in the or autumn or winter.

address: 13 Lincoln's Inn Fields, London, United Kingdom

Definitely worth a visit. The gift shop is pretty good as well!

name: energie Fitness Club Forest Hill
text: If you are looking for a corporate style gym with a pool, steam room and sauna etc etc. Look elsewhere. If you are looking for a local gym with friendly, helpful staff, a good range of equipment and machines as well as free weights (downstairs) then this is an ideal place. I have had a great experience at this gym - staff are friendly and dedicated. Most members (even the few muscle heads!) are pleasant welcoming and friendly. There is a very unique community/family feel among staff and members, The studio has regular classes (the usual: spin, pilates, yoga, zumba) and are free to members. When the studio is not in use, it is additional space for members to use. There are also regular social events occasionally at the gym and occasionally in the local area. Personal training is available. For what it is (a neighborhood gym) and for the price and membership deals, this is an excellent place. However, not a huge corporate style health and fitness center, so if you want and can afford that, go pay for the additional but unnecessary extras! All the essentials are here for you to get a good workout and experience and meet your goals.

name: Kumon Beckenham Study Centre
text: As the retiring Kumon instructor for this study centre, having established the Kumon programme in both the Beckenham and Crystal Palace areas, I wish the new team every success in their quest to build upon the legacy they have inherited from us. Together with the instructors at Forest Hill and Bromley we have seen the reputation of Kumon grow from very modest beginnings over the course of some 20 years (17 of these being at The Azelia Hall in Beckenham). Many enjoyable years have passed since we opened our first Kumon centre from our living room, during which time we have had the privilege of watching so many students grow from children into assured, talented adults. We look forward to hearing of their great deeds in life!

name: Kumon Beckenham Study Centre
text: Sunny morning in Japan! Kumon started in Japan 60 years ago and is now very popular in five continents, so I will say no more. Beckenham instructor is one of my best friends and we met and worked in an international company for years. I can see Kumon's shadow from him. It was actual myself who told him about the Kumon programmes and he was so interested, now he ended up running a Kumon centre. I wish him all the best and I am convinced that with his solid education and teaching background, his Beckenham centre will be doing very well.
